        <h2>A thought exercise on web performance</h2>
        <div class="description">
Nobody likes to wait. I have been thinking about this thought exercise for the past few weeks as I challenge myself to optimize my and my clients sites: What does site speed and page weight really feel like?
        </div>
        <div class="description">
          The exercise is to compare site speed to things in everyday life in order to make performance and performance increases more understandable and explainable. Starting with a baseline to compare to (outside of my own clients) the median time to interact for many of the top 100 e-commerce sites is 5.2 seconds. <strong>Perspective</strong> - most players in the NFL can run the 40 yard dash faster than this averaging 4.8 seconds.
        </div>
        <a href="http://m0.joe.ie/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/jadeveon-clowney-40-yard-dash.gif" target="_blank" class="ui segment large image blog-image">
          <img src="http://m0.joe.ie/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/jadeveon-clowney-40-yard-dash.gif" title="40 yard dash gif" alt="40 yard dash gif">
        </a>
        <div class="description">
          That seems fast but the gold standard for most UI development is 3 seconds. This is the time between believing work is being done and lost attention or frustration of nothing seeming to be done. We’ve upgraded from an NFL defensive end to the time it takes a Ferrari 458 to go from 0 to 60 mph. This may seem faster but if you are waiting for something to be done on the internet our expectations are even higher. <strong>Perspective</strong> - if webpages were blank until time to interact, browsing the web might be as painful as watching this timer every time you navigated pages (fortunately they are not!).
        </div>
        <br/>
