Two questions I asked myself after this thought exercise were “Is the web really that slow for me?” and “What would a performance improvement feel like?”
        </div>
        <h2>Is the web really that slow?</h2>
        <div class="description">
          Yes! Often times we forget that in urban america we are not the norm. Especially as a web developer often in offices with fiber internet connections and high bandwidth rates, I find myself in an extreme when it comes to high performance internet. I recently traveled and worked from coffee shops and on campus guest internet at my university and found myself amazed at the slower speeds (for many reasons including throttling, geolocation, censoring, ad blocking…); it was noticeable. Also during that trip I found myself loading sites on my phone when I normally would browse at home and found the mobile speeds more notably frustrating when I had work to do and was focused. My home internet is around 100Mbs but LTE at my house is around 15Mbs. <strong>Perspective</strong> - this is comparable to the difference between the speed of a baseball thrown by an eight year old verses the top speed of an MLB pitcher's fastball!
        </div>
        <div class="description">
          So what does a performance improvement feel like? It depends. If your website is at the gold standard (3 seconds time to interact) and you make a 1 second improvement your site may still feel slow but would be somewhat noticible (greater than 20 percent difference). For Example: people blink on average 15-20 times per minute so you are still catching people before they can blink. A gain such as this might not be noticeable unless compared directly against competition or side by side with an older version; it is much more visible when you go the other direction though. A 1 second slowdown can wreak havoc on the perception of performance, taking your site from inside the attention window to outside. <strong>Perspective</strong> - I encourage you to play with this difference in the form of frames per second using this tool <a href="https://frames-per-second.appspot.com/" target="_blank">Frames Per Second</a> that allows you to animate things at various speeds.
        </div>
        <div class="description">
          Focusing on perception and performance is critical in the modern web as we move to more mobile infrastructure and higher standards. Simply by the math if a user is on your site an average of 1 minute, visits 5 pages and your page load time gets improved from 4 seconds to 3 seconds, you save your users around 10% of their time but most importantly keep them captivated and flowing through your site instead of looking away or going elsewhere. Math can show you the percentages and impact on conversion but sometimes it takes real world examples to bring awareness to even the most subtle changes that have a large impact on your site’s success.
        </div>
